title: I think I know why the eye-tracker y-pos kept getting shifted:
message:
I think I know why the eye-tracker y-pos kept getting shifted:

moving left/right does not cause one side to mirror the other side, because the negativity of one side is just the "relaxing" of the outer muscle--and the relaxation amount is less than the tensing amount of the other side.

So it sees the left/right as having a net positive result, causing my naive code to think the eye was looking up some.

See here for illustration of eye muscles: http://www.innerbody.com/image/nerv08.html

title: * Readme improved a bit.
message:
* Readme improved a bit.

Note that if you use external folders as mentioned last commit, and you want changes to those external folder's js files to reflect in your app, you have to either copy the contents each time into the node_modules folder, or do a directory-level "hard-link clone" from the external folder to that node_modules location. Whenever you add a new JS file that needs tracking, you also need to redo this directory-level "hard-link clone". (but at least not after every file change)

For knowing what I mean by that phrase (and for doing the deed itself pretty easily on Windows), see here: http://schinagl.priv.at/nt/hardlinkshellext/linkshellextension.html#hardlinkclones

title: * React-native-lib-muse is now imported directly from it's main repo, rather…
message:
* React-native-lib-muse is now imported directly from it's main repo, rather than having a separate copy in the node_modules folder. (this makes it much easier to make changes, without going out-of-sync with main repo)
* UserConfig.json file can now be created. You can have it contain these strings, which are self-explanatory: "reactNativeLibMuse_external: true", "mpChartLib_external: true" (they have it look for a dedicated folder for the project repo, in the grandparent folder of this project's root folder, instead of looking in the node_modules folder and/or the cloud)
